class Solution {
    vector<int> parent;
    vector<int> rankk;

    // Find the root of the set containing element x with path compression.
    int find(int x) {
        if (parent[x] == x) {
            return x;
        }
        return parent[x] = find(parent[x]);
    }

    // Union two sets containing elements x and y.
    void unionSet(int x, int y) {
        x = find(x);
        y = find(y);

        if (x == y) {
            return;  // x and y are already in the same set.
        }

        // Union by rank to keep the tree flat.
        if (rankk[x] > rankk[y]) {
            parent[y] = x;
        } else if (rankk[x] < rankk[y]) {
            parent[x] = y;
        } else {
            parent[y] = x;
            rankk[x]++;
        }
    }

initilaize par array(){
par[i] = i;

};



What â€œrankâ€ actually tracks

The rank is an estimate of the height of the tree â€” not an exact size, not number of nodes.
We use it only to decide which tree should go under which.

ðŸªµ Case 1: Ranks are different

If one tree is taller (say rank[px] > rank[py]),
we make the shorter one a child of the taller one.
ðŸ‘‰ The height of the taller tree does not increase, so its rank stays the same.

No height increase = no rank increase âœ…

ðŸŒ³ Case 2: Ranks are equal

Letâ€™s say:

Tree A â†’ rank = 2
Tree B â†’ rank = 2


Both trees have equal height.
Now, if you attach one root under the other â€”
the new treeâ€™s height increases by 1.

So new height = old height + 1 â†’
ðŸ‘‰ rank of the new root must increase by 1.




